40|$|Abstract—Two {{directional}} UWB <b>monopole</b> <b>antennas</b> are proposed. It {{is shown}} that a design methodology for omnidirectional UWB rectangular planar <b>monopole</b> <b>antennas</b> can be applied for directional ones. The directional features are taken by introducing a slanting angle between the radiator and the ground plane. The slanting angle also {{plays a role in}} the low cutoff frequency, and it is considered in a proposed equation to determine that frequency. For the two UWB antennas the radiators have a rectangular shape, and the bandwidth is extended by choosing beveling angle and an appropriate height-width ratio. The developed antennas have a bandwidth wider than 10 GHz for a reflection coefficient lower than − 10 dB. The directional radiation pattern has an average gain of 5 dB. 1...|$|R
40|$|The {{decoupling}} {{between two}} <b>monopole</b> <b>antennas,</b> {{to be used}} as transmit and receive elements, placed closely, is a highly important issue in many applications, such as continuous wave (CW) radars, active repeaters, decoys and full duplex transceivers. Depending on the application, a minimum decoupling is required to achieve proper operation, which is usually in the range - 60 dB to - 90 dB. Considering the fact that, in most cases, omni directional coverage is required, the case of <b>monopole</b> <b>antennas</b> of quarter wavelength is considered. Additionally, optimization routines were implemented, taking in account the geometrical characteristics of the antenna in order to control the bandwidth of operation around 10. 25 GHz, leading to either broadband or narrowband behavior, as well as the antennas' gain...|$|R
